{"badges":["TM5","TM6"],"preparations":[{"title":"To Serve","content":["Place Parmesan and lemon peel in mixing bowl then grate <nobr>15 sec\/speed 10<\/nobr>. Transfer to a bowl and set aside.","Place 250 g spinach in mixing bowl and wilt <nobr>2 min\/100°C\/speed 1<\/nobr>.","Add remaining 250 g spinach then, while stirring with spatula through hole in mixing bowl lid, wilt <nobr>5 min\/100°C\/speed 1<\/nobr>. Drain through simmering basket, squeezing out excess water, then set aside.","Place flour, semolina, ricotta, reserved drained spinach, reserved grated Parmesan, egg, nutmeg, salt, pepper and chilli flakes in mixing bowl then mix <nobr>20 sec\/speed 4<\/nobr>. Scrape down sides of mixing bowl with spatula then mix again <nobr>20 sec\/speed 4<\/nobr>.","Dust semolina over a large baking tray. Use 2 dessertspoons to shape mixture into small quenelles, about the size of a walnut, then place on prepared tray and cover in semolina.","Bring a pan of salted water to the boil then add malfatti in batches and cook for 2-3 minutes. Remove with a slotted spoon when they float to the surface. Drain in a colander then cover with foil to keep warm while cooking remaining malfatti."]}],"ingredients":[{"title":"","content":["120 g Parmesan cheese, cut in pieces (2 cm)","½ lemon, thin peelings of skin only","500 g fresh spinach leaves","40 g plain flour","200 g semolina, plus extra for dusting","250 g ricotta cheese","1 large egg","¼ tsp ground nutmeg","1 tsp fine sea salt, or to taste, plus extra for cooking","2 pinches ground black pepper, or to taste","2 pinches dried chilli flakes"]},{"title":"To Serve","content":["1 Tbsp olive oil, for frying","100 g salted butter, diced, for frying","10 - 12 fresh sage leaves, for frying","fine sea salt, to taste","dried chilli flakes, for serving (optional)"]}],"id":"r261969","imageLink":"https:\/\/2.bp.blogspot.com\/-PHpRo4ZnbGU\/XZMudSx_LJI\/AAAAAAAAaFg\/KLIQabnJToUnFk1F7oZkz7mfVKEKgd2lgCLcBGAsYHQ\/s1600\/0_IQHDHicZoNAy4IVS.png","title":"Spinach and Ricotta Malfatti - Malfatti di spinaci e ricotta","publishedAt":"2018-05-28T00:00:00Z","nutrition":{"protein":"4.4 g","fat":"5.3 g","uom":"per 1 piece","carbohydrates":"5.1 g","calories":"368 kJ \/ 88 kcal"},"usefulItems":"large baking tray, saucepan, slotted spoon, colander, aluminium foil, frying pan, hob","hintsAndTricks":["Malfatti, literally ‘badly made’ in Italian, are small finger-shaped dumplings made from spinach and cheese. This humble dish is believed to have been invented by mistake, when leftover ravioli filling was reformed into dumplings by a resourceful chef. With spinach giving them a distinctive green colouring, the dumplings are served coated in a sage butter and eaten as part of an antipasti spread, or covered with a rich tomato sauce and enjoyed as a hearty main meal.","To make this recipe suitable for vegetarians, substitute the Parmesan cheese for a vegetarian hard cheese."],"basicInfo":["medium","35m","45m","40 pieces"]}